docs.abstract: The State Department plans to pay for a conference in Washington for all its chiefs of mission while most of its employees go without pay.
docs.snippet: The State Department plans to pay for a conference in Washington for all its chiefs of mission while most of its employees go without pay.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The State Department plans to fly all of its ambassadors and other top diplomatic envoys from around the world into Washington next week for a two-day conference, even if the continuing partial government shutdown continues.

headline.main: U.S. Ambassadors Worldwide Are Summoned to D.C. Forum Despite Shutdown
headline.print_headline: A Gathering of U.S. Ambassadors That Now Doesn’t Seem Like Such a Good Idea

docs.abstract: The hiring of Stefan Passantino, a deputy counsel who was in charge of ethics policy, is part of the strategy by the White House and the company to counter an expected onslaught from House Democrats.
docs.snippet: The hiring of Stefan Passantino, a deputy counsel who was in charge of ethics policy, is part of the strategy by the White House and the company to counter an expected onslaught from House Democrats.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Trump Organization has hired a former White House lawyer to handle inquiries from the Democrat-led House, two people familiar with the situation said on Friday, part of the strategy by the White House and the company to counter an expected onslaught of requests and subpoenas.

headline.main: Trump Organization Hires Ex-White House Lawyer to Handle Congressional Inquiries

docs.abstract: Impeachment? Tax returns? Jail time? The Democrat-controlled House of Representatives will no doubt investigate many aspects of Mr. Trump’s administration and life. But some of its most aggressive goals will be difficult, if not unlikely, to achieve.

docs.lead_paragraph: With the House of Representatives now under Democratic control and the gavel in Speaker Nancy Pelosi’s hands, some of President Trump’s critics are eagerly anticipating a surge of congressional investigations.

headline.main: The Limits to Democratic Actions Against Trump
headline.print_headline: Power of the Majority Only Goes So Far  Against the President

docs.abstract: If the court is to hear major cases this term on immigration, transgender service in the military, gay rights, abortion or guns, it must act soon.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Supreme Court added eight cases to its docket on Friday, including ones on how gun laws apply to undocumented immigrants and whether the police may have blood drawn from unconscious motorists suspected of drunken driving.

headline.main: Supreme Court Takes Eight Cases, but Doesn’t Act on Some Big Ones
headline.print_headline: Justices Take Up Eight New Cases, but Avoid Some Big Issues for Now

docs.abstract: Federal tax revenues declined in 2018 while economic growth accelerated, undercutting the Trump administration’s insistence that the $1.5 trillion tax package would pay for itself.
docs.snippet: Federal tax revenues declined in 2018 while economic growth accelerated, undercutting the Trump administration’s insistence that the $1.5 trillion tax package would pay for itself.
docs.lead_paragraph: It’s time to put to rest any notion that President Trump’s signature tax cuts are paying for themselves. Anyone who says otherwise is lying with numbers.

headline.main: It’s Official: The Trump Tax Cuts Didn’t Pay for Themselves in Year One
headline.print_headline: Tax Cut Paid for Itself? It Isn’t Even Close

docs.abstract: Delayed mortgage applications, missed paychecks and stymied farmers are among the repercussions of a shutdown with no end in sight.
docs.snippet: Delayed mortgage applications, missed paychecks and stymied farmers are among the repercussions of a shutdown with no end in sight.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The impact of a partial government shutdown began to ripple across the economy as it stretched into Day 17, with mortgage applications delayed, public companies unable to get approval to raise capital and thousands of Secret Service agents expected to show up for work without pay.

headline.main: As Government Shutdown Persists, Americans Feel the Bite
headline.print_headline: Impasse Starting To Leave a Mark On the Economy

docs.abstract: Surging newsprint costs are adding to the woes of struggling local newspapers, forcing them to reduce staff and publication days.
docs.snippet: Surging newsprint costs are adding to the woes of struggling local newspapers, forcing them to reduce staff and publication days.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration’s decision to impose tariffs on Canadian newsprint is hastening the demise of local newspapers across the country, forcing already-struggling publications to cut staff, reduce the number of days they print and, in at least one case, shutter entirely.

headline.main: Trump’s Tariffs on Canadian Newsprint Hasten Local Newspapers’ Demise

docs.abstract: A cluster of activist Democrats largely cruising toward House seats has dared to breach what has been an almost inviolable orthodoxy on both sides of the aisle.
docs.snippet: A cluster of activist Democrats largely cruising toward House seats has dared to breach what has been an almost inviolable orthodoxy on both sides of the aisle.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — One Democratic House candidate has pledged that she will vote against bills that include aid to Israel, denouncing what she saw as the “injustice” of Israel’s treatment of the Palestinians. Another wrote that “Israel has hypnotized the world” with its “evil doings.”

headline.main: A New Wave of Democrats Tests the Party’s Blanket Support for Israel
headline.print_headline: New Wave of Democrats Tests the Party’s Blanket Support for Israel
